As the epitome of optimistic narrative-building spectacle, the 1939 New Yor=
k World=E2=80=99s Fair was a turning point in global futurism, as it was th=
e first Expo to (literally) look toward "The World of Tomorrow."=C2=A0
Its slogan: "Dawn of a New Day.=E2=80=9D
For two years, 44 million people =E2=80=94 including people affected by the=
 Great Depression =E2=80=94 experienced new scientific and technological fr=
ontiers for the first time. Watch this newsreel from 1939:=C2=A0
=C2=A0The exhibition promoted the harmony of countries and governance world=
wide; the sharing of food, dance, and culture; the revival of heroic, regal=
 art; and the breakthrough entrepreneurship of the time. It emphasized =E2=
=80=94 through amusement, entertainment, exhibitions, and experiences =E2=
=80=94 that science is for all, that the future can be built, and that we c=
an collectively be amazing.=C2=A0
The 1939 Fair was based on the concept of =E2=80=9CX of Tomorrow=E2=80=9D: =
technology, science, transportation, communication, food, government, commu=
nity interests, amusement, etc.=C2=A0
The Fair celebrated =E2=80=9CTomorrow=E2=80=9D by showcasing the futuristic=
 appliances available =E2=80=9CToday.=E2=80=9D Attendees saw newly adopted =
innovations like television, mass electric power, and cars next to longer-t=
erm possibilities such as personal robotics, space travel, and more.
Yet, it wasn=E2=80=99t just a science fair. It was a means to show how prog=
ress would shape daily life. Companies showed off their newest toys and the=
ir wildest ideas side-by-side:=C2=A0
General Motors showed off a model city designed for cars with super-highway=
s from coast to coast and no red lights in the Transportation Zone.=C2=A0
Ford also displayed some of its newest vehicle designs in the Transportatio=
n Zone.=C2=A0
General Electric introduced the world to the fluorescent light bulb and equ=
ipped an auditorium with a new invention: air conditioning.=C2=A0
Westinghouse unveiled the seven-foot-tall =E2=80=9CElektro the Moto-Man,=E2=
=80=9D a personal robot that could talk and perform tasks for regular consu=
mers.=C2=A0
In the Communications Zone, AT&T showed off a mechanized, synthetic voice a=
ssistant that could speak to fairgoers.=C2=A0
IBM unveiled new devices of its own, such as the electric typewriter and an=
 electric calculator.=C2=A0
RCA showed FM radio, the fax machine, and the television. Their technology =
was used to televise Fair events and even made President Franklin Delano Ro=
osevelt the first president to be televised.=C2=A0
Heinz laid the blueprint for baby food.=C2=A0
Many of these inventions seem old hat now, others are just arriving today, =
and we=E2=80=99re still waiting for some 84 years later, a testament to the=
 exhibitors' mix of can-do spirit and optimism.=C2=A0
The General Motors Pavilion, within which was Futurama, a model city that o=
nlookers viewed from above
The Fair embodied a long-lost American ideal: the unconditional belief that=
 science and technology fuel economic prosperity and personal freedom. Caug=
ht between the Great Depression and World War II, the Fair was the antidote=
 to misery and chaos. It gave people hope.=C2=A0
The New York World=E2=80=99s Fair Committee intended the event to not be fa=
r-future speculation but rather a realistic, definite-optimistic vision: =
=E2=80=9CThe main purpose of the New York World Fair of 1939 [was] to show =
the tools of today with which America is preparing to build a better world =
of tomorrow.=E2=80=9D It provided a search for a =E2=80=9Cuseable Future [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/c2181cb6-9664-407e-bdeb-4f27aeb88b94?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (with a capita=
l =E2=80=98F=E2=80=99)=E2=80=9D and of hope, possibility, and dynamism in t=
he face of catastrophe.=C2=A0
The =E2=80=9Cusable Future=E2=80=9D piece indisputably left an enduring cul=
tural and spiritual legacy. This specific World=E2=80=99s Fair combined a f=
uture-facing ideological construct, trade show, League of Nations, amusemen=
t park, and utopian community to uphold the prophecy that an abundant, free=
 society can be achieved through technology. Even the social norms, art, an=
d architecture were stylistically advanced and unlike anything of the time,=
 such as the Trylon and Perisphere.=C2=A0
The 1930s through 1960s were a Golden Age of World=E2=80=99s Fairs, too. Th=
e USA hosted other major World=E2=80=99s Fair expositions: the 1933 Chicago=
 Century of Progress Exposition, the 1939 San Francisco Golden Gate Interna=
tional Exposition, and the 1962 Seattle Century 21 Exposition. America ende=
d its run of hosting such events with a bang: the infamous 1964 New York Wo=
rld's Fair.
As a collaboration between Robert Moses (yes, the Power Broker) and Walt Di=
sney, the 1964 World=E2=80=99s Fair embodied =E2=80=9CPeace Through Underst=
anding" and dedicated itself to "Man's Achievement on a Shrinking Globe in =
an Expanding Universe.=E2=80=9D This Fair reintroduced consumers to some of=
 the era=E2=80=99s most impactful inventions: computers with keyboards, tel=
etype machines, telephone modems, Saturn V=E2=80=99s engines, Gemini spacec=
raft, lunar rovers, satellites, videoconferencing, animatronics, futuristic=
 homes, undersea hotels, electric cities, nuclear power plants, and color T=
V. Corporations again took the lead on this narrative with grandiose exhibi=
ts such as:
General Motors=E2=80=99 Futurama displayed dioramas of a possible near-futu=
re society.=C2=A0
DuPont presented The Wonderful World of Chemistry.
Sinclair Oil Corporation sponsored Dinoland, featuring life-sized dinosaur =
replicas.=C2=A0
Bell System constructed the Ride of Communications.=C2=A0
General Electric sponsored the Carousel of Progress, where audience members=
 revolved around an audio-animatronic presentation of the progress of elect=
ricity in the home.=C2=A0
Disney laid the foundation of the entire Fair and specifically designed Pep=
si=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CIt's a Small World,=E2=80=9D General Electric's Progr=
esslan, Ford=E2=80=99s Magic Skyway, and the first audio-animatronic presen=
tation ever in Illinois Pavilion=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CGreat Moments with Mr. =
Lincoln.=E2=80=9D
The Fairs were moments when the world rejoiced in a collective appreciation=
 of science, technology, and global unity. From a macro view, America saw s=
o much progress during the main stint of the Fairs (1851 - 1964). Despite t=
he crazy backdrop of global events, people saw their day-to-day lives rapid=
ly improving (think about the home in the 1890s versus the 1960s). Food, tr=
ansportation, cities, medicines, electronics, energy, everything. The best =
part: everyone felt and saw these advances. Things were booming. You didn=
=E2=80=99t have to look very hard to see the future improving.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s that exact narrative that made the Fairs so special. People re=
alized that we are capable of so much more, and we can achieve it. The 1933=
 Chicago and 1939 New York fairs pulled America, culturally and emotionally=
, out of the Great Depression; the 1964 Fair spread harmony in the globaliz=
ed Space Age. Better yet, they literally brought science to people=E2=80=99=
s doorsteps with Elektro, Westinghouse=E2=80=99s voice-controlled personal =
robot that could walk, talk, and smoke a cigarette.=C2=A0
Westinghouse toured =E2=80=9Chim=E2=80=9D around the country to get people =
excited about the potential to have a robot in their house. Check it out he=
re:=C2=A0
The last World=E2=80=99s Fair in the United States took place, ironically, =
in 1984, that dystopian year foretold in science fiction. Facing competitio=
n from a technology previewed at the 1939 World=E2=80=99s Fair =E2=80=93 th=
e television =E2=80=93=C2=A0 and from the architect of the 1964 World=E2=80=
=99s Fair =E2=80=93 Disney=E2=80=99s EPCOT =E2=80=93 the 1984 Louisiana Wor=
ld Exposition ended in bankruptcy. But a lot has happened since 1984, and t=
he future looks brighter now than it did then. It=E2=80=99s time for a new =
World=E2=80=99s Fair.=C2=A0
To that end, we=E2=80=99re particularly excited about our friend Cam Wiese=
=E2=80=99s World=E2=80=99s Fair Co [ https://substack.com/redirect/12360aac=
-6117-40c0-b9c9-49c36754941f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
By the end of the decade, Cam & Co. plan to =E2=80=9Copen the gates to the =
next great World=E2=80=99s Fair,=E2=80=9D showcasing advances across a numb=
er of the categories we write about here in Not Boring.=C2=A0
Planning a whole World=E2=80=99s Fair is a decade-long journey, but in the =
interim, there are opportunities to draw inspiration from the Fairs to crea=
te experiences around new technologies that let people feel the magic for t=
hemselves and picture how their life might change for the better. It=E2=80=
=99s not a coincidence that art kicked off the AI renaissance and that GPT =
reached 100 million users faster than any other company when OpenAI put it =
behind a familiar chat interface. The technology moved from research paper =
to spectacle.=C2=A0
Founders, leaders, and other pioneers should take the helm just as they did=
 in the Fairs. We all have a moral imperative to make science fun.=C2=A0
I Have Seen the Future=C2=A0
Narratives are a double-edged sword. They can instill hope or fear. And the=
 fear side is sharper.=C2=A0
Think about the narratives that have broken through in the past few months.=
 War. Elon=E2=80=99s Twitter. The FTX Fraud. The Impending Recession. The C=
hinese Spy Balloon. Even Mr. Beast paying to cure blindness in 1,000 people=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/c01200c1-5a2a-4a43-907d-b9597d1c6cf5?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] made people=
 angry.=C2=A0
These are all important stories, and I=E2=80=99m not suggesting that they s=
houldn=E2=80=99t get coverage. They should. Skepticism is an important part=
 of pragmatic optimism, and good journalists play an important role. But th=
e balance is off. The Good Stories aren=E2=80=99t being told as loudly or a=
s compellingly as they could be.=C2=A0
In 2022 alone, we saw some crazy breakthroughs [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/c206a946-ce9a-4cc0-ad23-0fc74cd6f56c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that are already impacting people=E2=80=
=99s lives: the FDA approved 37 new drugs, bionic eyes restored blindness, =
cancer death rates decreased, Al-powered protein predictions were validated=
, malaria vaccine became twice as effective, a girl=E2=80=99s cancer was cu=
red with base editing, multiple rare disease advances were made, life was c=
reated without egg, sperm, or a womb, gene-editing got safer and more preci=
se, gene-therapy-based sickle cell anemia cure came about, spinal implants =
helped paralyzed people walk and swim, scientists achieved nuclear fusion i=
gnition, states green-lighted medical use of psilocybin, wastewater trackin=
g systems detected outbreaks in cities, perovskite-based solar cells broke =
the 30% efficiency barrier, new ways to prevent LDL (the leading cause of h=
eart attacks & strokes) went mainstream, large language models saw massive =
adoption, the James Webb Telescope revolutionized astronomy, an asteroid wa=
s redirected, and more. So. Much. More.=C2=A0
Sitting in the middle of all of this, trying desperately to keep up with th=
e frenzied pace of innovation, it=E2=80=99s hard not to see how the future =
will be better than the present, and that the present is better than the pa=
st.=C2=A0
But the stories we tell, the ones that people are listening to, paint a dif=
ferent picture. They ask, =E2=80=9CWhat could go wrong?=E2=80=9D instead of=
 =E2=80=9CHow can we work together to make this go right?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Stephenson had thoughts on why this is, too. Explaining why =E2=80=9CSpeaki=
ng broadly, the techno-optimism of the Golden Age of SF has given way to fi=
ction written in a generally darker, more skeptical and ambiguous tone,=E2=
=80=9D he wrote:
Believing we have all the technology we=E2=80=99ll ever need, we seek to dr=
aw attention to its destructive side effects. This seems foolish now that w=
e find ourselves saddled with technologies like Japan=E2=80=99s ramshackle =
1960s-vintage reactors at Fukushima when we have the possibility of clean n=
uclear fusion on the horizon. The imperative to develop new technologies an=
d implement them on a heroic scale no longer seems like the childish preocc=
upation of a few nerds with slide rules. It=E2=80=99s the only way for the =
human race to escape from its current predicaments. Too bad we=E2=80=99ve f=
orgotten how to do it.
That essay is from 2011, but a dozen years later, it seems as though we=E2=
=80=99ve remembered how to develop new technologies and implement them on a=
 heroic scale. The narrative just hasn=E2=80=99t caught up.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The other day, tongue in cheek, Packy tweeted a poll asking what finally go=
t the aliens interested enough in humans to reveal themselves:=C2=A0
Fusion, AGI, and interplanetary travel are three of the most common themes =
in sci-fi from any era. All three appear in Asimov=E2=80=99s The Last Quest=
ion [ https://substack.com/redirect/e3526c21-0078-4fdc-8efe-7a662ef32a2d?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. They=
=E2=80=99re humanity-altering technologies. In the past three months, durin=
g a period of doom and gloom and supposed stagnation, we=E2=80=99ve taken m=
eaningful steps closer to achieving all three. And the implications are goi=
ng to be confusing as hell to work through.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s where stories come in.=C2=A0
Those who understand today=E2=80=99s technology well enough to envision wor=
lds born of its extrapolations should do so. Write sci-fi, make movies, cre=
ate art, build monuments, bring back World=E2=80=99s Fairs.=C2=A0
We should return to the days of celebrating big achievements as they elicit=
 feelings of pride in the public towards doing impactful things. We should =
build more monuments [ https://substack.com/redirect/61e99287-cdec-49bd-ba4=
c-1fba92240fdc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ], new wonders of the world, and massive art installations. Statues =
of true heroes, structures like The Colosseum and the Taj Mahal, museums fu=
ll of art ahead of their time. Even amusement parks like Disney=E2=80=99s E=
PCOT (=E2=80=9C=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8BExperimental Prototype Community of Tomorr=
ow=E2=80=9D).
It=E2=80=99s not about blindly celebrating tech founders. It is possible to=
 be both optimistic and cautious.=C2=A0
And, it=E2=80=99s not about being =E2=80=9Cnicer=E2=80=9D to tech. Stories =
are simply a way to compress information and help people grok the positives=
 and wrestle with the negatives of everything going on. Negative stories ha=
ve a natural advantage; putting more effort into telling Good Stories would=
 help balance the scales. The impact of this cultural change would be immen=
se.
Humans need narratives to make sense of things. Stories help us understand =
what to do, what everyone else is doing, and how to do it. They ask, what i=
s possible? What needs to be done? What Can You Do For Your Country? They a=
re motivational, guiding, and inspiring. They are pure magic. They make the=
 pursuit of the impossible attractive and attainable.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s this great quote from Karen Armstrong in The Great Transfor=
mation [ https://substack.com/redirect/29a7d101-775f-4116-8784-80df30cd9659=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=
=80=9CUnless there is some kind of spiritual revolution that can keep abrea=
st of our technological genius, it is unlikely that we will save our planet=
=2E A purely rational education will not suffice.=E2=80=9D
I=E2=80=99d amend it in a couple of ways.=C2=A0
Unless there is some kind of narrative revolution that can keep abreast of =
our technological genius, it is unlikely that we will reach our full, amazi=
ng potential. A purely rational education will not suffice.
We need better sci-fi to guide builders who want to create a magnificent fu=
ture, and dazzling spectacles to let people picture themselves in it.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s time to tell Good Stories again.
Thanks to Rahul [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f1ae954-d2f9-44f4-a31f-0e7=
82fac9852?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] for writing an excellent piece, and to Dan [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/74839826-92c5-449a-8b31-8ff8b2aab7cf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your podcast feeds t=
his week, and in your inbox with a Weekly Dose of Optimism on Friday. Have =
a great week!=20
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

