04040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Fortu=
nately, humans long ago devised a tool to help us make sense of a confusing=
 world: </span><strong>narrative</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">We need knowledgeable people to tell Good Stories, to weave together all =
of the threads of the current state-of-the-art into compelling narratives t=
hat help clarify the future. Importantly, they need to help people understa=
nd the impact &#8211; good and bad, not just bad &#8211; that new technolog=
ies might have on their lives. As Einstein said, the achievements of scienc=
e (and technology) &#8220;must enter not only superficially but with their =
inner meaning: into the consciousness of people.&#8221; Research papers don=
&#8217;t worm into the consciousness of the people. Stories do.&#160;</p><p=
 style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 2=
0px 0;"><span>In </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/5aaea9=
5b-55b6-4798-b6a1-7f489aa431aa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: =
underline;">The Purpose of Technology</a></em><span>, Balaji puts the onus =
back on the technologists themselves.</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border=
-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: #=
404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left=
: 20px;"><em>We need to take time out of our busy days to make the case, re=
peatedly and with high production values, that technological progress is th=
e most important thing we can do for broad-based prosperity and economic gr=
owth, and for life itself.</em></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>That st=
arts with testing, drugs, treatments, and vaccines for COVID-19. But it goe=
s far beyond that. Put another way: we may not get life extension or the wh=
ole suite of transhumanist technologies (brain-machine interfaces, stem cel=
ls, CRISPR gene therapy, and more) unless you, personally, evangelize them =
online. Not just tweets, but articles. Not just articles, but videos. Not j=
ust videos, but feature films. And not just a few films, but an entire Netf=
lix original library's worth, a parallel tech media ecosystem full of inspi=
rational content for technological progressives. A lifetime's worth of cont=
ent that makes the case for immutable money, infinite frontier, artificial =
intelligence, and eternal life.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #40=
4040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Optimi=
stic storytelling can lift people out of their current circumstances and gi=
ve them hope for the future. If it worked during the Great Depression, it c=
an work today. As importantly, it can help rally people behind </span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/5b2b6ea4-e783-4f31-87bc-f74f5bde3aca?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D""=
 style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Good Quests</a><span=
>, remove barriers for those working to make a better future, and inspire t=
he next generation to dream bigger than their parents ever could.&#160;</sp=
an></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;">Today, we&#8217;ll focus on two forms of storytelling: Sci=
ence Fiction and Spectacle.&#160;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Science fiction speaks=
 to inventors, engineers, and scientists &#8211; the people building the fu=
ture. Spectacles help people experience what those futures might feel like =
for them.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-os=
x-font-smoothing: subpixel-antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: subpixel-an=
tialiased; color: #404040; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system=
, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Ap=
ple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; =
font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: =
relative;"><strong>Sci-Fi: Making the Frontier Not Boring&#160;</strong></h=
3><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;"><span>It&#8217;s hard to write a piece about optimistic storyte=
lling without discussing the genre that perfectly encapsulates it: science =
fiction. This genre is crucial to civilizational progress because </span><s=
trong>invention needs inspiration, and inspiration often comes from stories=
</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>At its best, optimistic sc=
i-fi makes people believe that the future is worth it and possible to achie=
ve. We had that in the 1930s-60s when many consumed content from the Golden=
 Age of science fiction, from works by Isaac Asimov, Arthur C. Clarke, and =
Robert Heinlein to Hollywood staples such as </span><em>The Jetsons, Star T=
rek, </em><span>and</span><em> 2001: A Space Odyssey</em><span>. These posi=
tive portrayals of technology were a force for good against the backdrop of=
 the Apollo Missions, the Atomic Age, the Computing Revolution, and other t=
ech trends. The best part: they inspired kids to become engineers, astrophy=
sicists, and future-builders.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In a 2011 </s=
pan><em>WIRED</em><span> essay, </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/=
redirect/cf2a0299-9316-4e63-ab75-e4f63e353105?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; te=
xt-decoration: underline;">Innovation Starvation</a><span>,</span></em><spa=
n> sci-fi author Neil Stephenson recounts attending that year&#8217;s Futur=
e Tense conference and bemoaning our seeming inability to get big stuff don=
e. The audience pushed back, believing, like we do, that science fiction ca=
n play a role in fixing the problem. Stephenson boiled what he heard down t=
o two theories:</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bd=
fc; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>&#8=
220;The </span><strong>Inspiration Theory</strong><span>. [Science fiction]=
 inspires people to choose science and engineering as careers. This much is=
 undoubtedly true, and somewhat obvious.</span></em></p><p style=3D"color: =
#404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-lef=
t: 20px;"><em><span>The </span><strong>Hieroglyph Theory</strong><span>. Go=
od [Science Fiction] supplies a plausible, fully thought-out picture of an =
alternate reality in which some sort of compelling innovation has taken pla=
ce. A good [science fiction] universe has a coherence and internal logic th=
at makes sense to scientists and engineers. Examples include Isaac Asimov&#=
8217;s robots, Robert Heinlein&#8217;s rocket ships, and William Gibson&#82=
17;s cyberspace. As Jim Karkanias of Microsoft Research puts it, such icons=
 serve as hieroglyphs &#8212; simple, recognizable symbols on whose signifi=
cance everyone agrees.&#8221;</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color=
: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>A=
s science and technology have become more complex, according to Stephenson,=
 each individual researcher and engineer is left responsible for a thinner =
and thinner slice of the overall project. In </span><em><a href=3D"https://=
substack.com/redirect/45d6ee3e-6ea4-4fb1-a7db-fdc0e11388ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color=
: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Centralization vs. Decentralization=
: Two Centuries of Authority in Design</a></em><span>, Sm&#225;ri McCarthy =
wrote of workers during the Industrial Revolution, &#8220;From the craftsme=
n they were, people were reduced to mere automata to which meaningless and =
repetitive tasks were assigned &#8211; so as to ensure the production and m=
anufacturing of goods in the context of large industrial facilities.&#8221;=
 Stephenson identifies the same issue two centuries later, and a layer of a=
bstraction higher: even those designing the machines have been reduced to m=
ere automata.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s where practical techno=
-optimistic sci-fi comes in:</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid=
 #67bdfc; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><sp=
an>The fondness that many such people have for SF [science fiction] reflect=
s, in part, the usefulness of an over-arching narrative that supplies them =
and their colleagues with a shared vision. Coordinating their efforts throu=
gh a command-and-control management system is a little like trying to run a=
 modern economy out of a Politburo. </span><strong>Letting them work toward=
 an agreed-on goal is something more like a free and largely self-coordinat=
ed market of ideas.&#160;</strong></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: =
#404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Stephenso=
n&#8217;s take challenges writers, poets, filmmakers, and other creatives t=
o start pulling their weight and supplying big visions that help the doers =
