rong><span> laid the blueprint for baby food.&#160;</span></p></li></ul><p =
style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">Many of these inventions seem old hat now, others are just arriving =
today, and we&#8217;re still waiting for some 84 years later, a testament t=
o the exhibitors' mix of can-do spirit and optimism.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><em=
><strong>The General Motors Pavilion, within which was Futurama, a model ci=
ty that onlookers viewed from above</strong></em></p><p style=3D"color: #40=
4040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The Fa=
ir embodied a long-lost American ideal: </span><strong>the unconditional be=
lief that science and technology fuel economic prosperity and personal free=
dom.</strong><span> Caught between the Great Depression and World War II, t=
he Fair was the antidote to misery and chaos. It gave people hope.&#160;</s=
pan></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The New York World&#8217;s Fair Committee intended =
the event to not be far-future speculation but rather a </span><strong>real=
istic, definite-optimistic vision</strong><span>: &#8220;The main purpose o=
f the New York World Fair of 1939 [was] to show the tools of today with whi=
ch America is preparing to build a better world of tomorrow.&#8221; It prov=
ided a search for a &#8220;</span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/=
